04467nam a22006975i 9781442685659DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426856597 a10.3138/97814426856592doi  a(DE-B1597)497106  a(OCoLC)1078914411  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD6099 -- S76 2007eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a331.4/1204209711 aStephen, Jennifer Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPick One Intelligent Girl :bEmployability, Domesticity and the Gendering of Canada's Welfare State, 1939-1947 /cJennifer Anne Stephen. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Gender and History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. ‘I Want You to Pick One Intelligent Girl’: Mobilizing Canada’s Womanpower -- t2. The National Selective Service Women’s Division and the Management of Women War Workers -- t3. The Psychologist at War: Assessing and Recruiting for the Canadian Women’s Army Corps -- t4. Preparing for the Peace: The Demobilization of Women Workers -- t5. ‘An Aptitude Test Is in Your Best Interest’: Canada’s Employment Charter for Women Veterans -- t6. The Return to Domesticity: Canada’s Womanhood in Training -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tSTUDIES IN GENDER AND HISTORY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the tumultuous formative years of the Canadian welfare state, many women rose through the ranks of the federal civil service to oversee the massive recruitment of Canadian women to aid in the Second World War. Ironically, it became the task of these same female mandarins to encourage women to return to the household once the war was over. Pick One Intelligent Girl reveals the elaborate psychological, economic, and managerial techniques that were used to recruit and train women for wartime military and civilian jobs, and then, at war's end, to move women out of the labour force altogether.Negotiating the fluid boundaries of state, community, industry, and household, and drawing on a wide range of primary sources, Jennifer A. Stephen illustrates how women's relationships to home, work, and nation were profoundly altered during this period. She demonstrates how federal officials enlisted the help of a new generation of 'experts' to entrench a two-tiered training and employment system that would become an enduring feature of the Canadian state.This engaging study not only adds to the debates about the gendered origins of Canada's welfare state, it also makes an important contribution to Canadian social history, labour and gender studies, sociology, and political science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSex discrimination in employmentzCanada. 0aWelfare statezCanada. 0aWomenxEmploymentxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xWar workzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xWomenzCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268565940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442685659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685659.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK